title: For Sale:  Flak jacket withKevlar panels
postcontent:
German flak jacket with Kevlar panels. Fits up to 46" chest.  Here are some specs, info I found on it 

This surplus German flak jacket is a versatile piece of protective clothing and  an authentic German military surplus item. These flak jackets were originally designed for and used by members of the German heer, or army, which is one of the five service branches that makes up the Bundeswehr, or unified armed forces of Germany. The flak jacket appears to have been previously issued, it remains in good condition and ready to continue service.
This surplus German flak jacket is Constructed from Kevlar® paneling contained in a nylon cloth carrier, the flak jacket is designed to offer protection from shrapnel, fragmentation, debris and other indirect projectiles to the chest, back, sides and shoulders. The easy-to-wear vest features Velcro® closures that are located on the left shoulder and both hips. Additionally, there is a large, expandable front pocket and rings located on both the front and back of the jacket for carrying additional gear. Not satisfied with the level of protection offered? The surplus German flak jacket includes a zippered closure for the insertion and removal of Kevlar® paneling and other plates.
Features the Flecktarn camouflage pattern. Flecktarn is a multicolor disruptive camouflage pattern, generally utilizing three or more colors. This particular pattern was designed for use in temperate woodland terrains, though by varying the colors, it is adaptable to other backdrops.

The surplus German flak jacket is a great choice for:
- Paintball and airsoft
- Costumes
- Reenactments
- Collections
Much more…

*NEW* Vest official specs:   PROTECTS AGAINST LEVEL IIA THREATS. This body armor protects against 9mm Full Metal  Jacketed Round Nose (FMJ RN) bullets, with nominal masses of 8.0 g (124 gr) impacting at  a minimum velocity of 332 m/s (1090 ft/s) or less, and .40 S&W caliber Full Metal  Jacketed (FMJ) bullets, with nominal masses of 11.7 g (180 gr) impacting at a minimum  velocity of 312 m/s (1025 ft/s) 357 MAG JSP, 158 GR at (1250 Ft/s) and all lower  ballistic threats. With complete full side, front, back, shoulder and collar coverage.  Includes one camouflage, three point, Velcro adjustable, outerwear carrier with Velcro  abdominal security strap attached inside of carrier, and six, removable, Kevlar ballistic  panels: one in the front portion; one in the back portion; one in each shoulder  attachment; and two in the collar assembly. Velcro fasteners over left shoulder, and both  sides.All panels are  manufactured with 13 layers of lightweight, high-tenacity Kevlar  129  fabric and are each enclosed in a sealed water repellent heavy nylon cover. Conforms to EN ISO 14876-1-2002 General requirements (ISO FDIS 14876-1 2002)
As stated in the specs, this vest uses 13 layers of kevlar 129, which is a higher quality than traditional kevlar 29 vests.  Kevlar 29 is usually found in older American flak vests and older bulletproof vests.  It has about 20% less tensile strength than kevlar 129.  This usually equates to needing more layers to accomplish the same amount of bullet resistance vs the german vests.
Couple that with Europe’s higher standard for backface deformation and you have something that is effectively extremely overbuilt for flak and comes out to be approximately a level IIA quality vest.
Things that effect ballistic Kevlar over time: As a rule, Kevlar is very durable and ages very well.  However, there are certain things which can vastly reduce the function of Kevlar by thirty or more percent.  The first is ultraviolet damage.  If the panels were stored outdoors for an extended period (look for sun-bleached covers), you might want to discard the panels or find an alternate use for  them.  The second is water damage.  Kevlar absorbs moisture.  This absorption means that the water will stay in the fibers and reduce it’s tensile strength.  
Luckily, the Germans considered this and built extremely heavy duty vinyl covers for the interior ballistic panels that are both water and UV resistant.  

Real world testing:  Now don’t take my word for it; numerous tests have been done by members of the community which validate the properties of this armor.  you can utube it to find out more about it.

postcontent: This Winchester Model 62A hosts the 23" round blued barrel, magazine tube, walnut stock and forearm, open sights, slide action and all in the famous .22 S, L, LR caliber. The serial number of 353331 indicates a production date of 1956. This is an excellent Winchester Model 62A with the original and rare picture box and paperwork. This Winchester is in near mint condition. The bluing is excellent with deep bluing remaining, very little thinning on the high edges and slide area with very little handling marks (see pictures). The bluing rates at 98% condition. The wood is in excellent condition with no cracks, no chips, no breaks, no splits and no major gouges. The wood only shows a few very minor handling marks. The wood rates at 98% condition. There are no extra holes drilled in this Winchester anywhere. The bore is clean and bright with crisp rifling grooves and well defined lands. The proof marks and barrel stampings are crisp. This Winchester is clean, original and complete. This is one of the nicest Model 62A rifles I have seen. It is in excellent condition. The rare picture box is also in very good condition considering the age. The box shows some minor storage wear but is solid and intact. The box is complete with a nice readable label, all the inner packaging and all the paperwork. The paperwork includes the brochure, the hang tag, warranty card, the hunters safety pamphlet and the three original targets that all came with the Winchester in the box. All the paperwork is in good to excellent condition. This is a very rare opportunity to own a complete Winchester package complete with the matching picture box and paperwork. This Winchester is in fantastic condition and will be an excellent investment. This Winchester will only increase in value if well cared for as it has been. title: For Sale:  CMMG 5.56 NATO 1/7 twist AR-15 package deal! Super Reliable!
location: North High Point, Greensboro, North Carolina
postcontent:
This carbine has CMMG upper and lower, 16” barrel, with standard front sight and Magpul folding rear sight, compact 1-4 x 24 scope with illuminated mil-dot reticle, 2 Magpul Pmags, ambidextrous single point sling, and tactical soft case.

This carbine has been designed and built for reliability.  Do an internet search on ‘so, you want to buy an AR-15, huh?) and you will be led to a thread in forums.officer.com, where the specifications and features that lead to reliability are discussed.  The author of the thread compared brands of AR-15 carried on duty by police officers and ranked this CMMG as equal to Colt, LMT, and Noveske, and ahead of S&W, Sabre Defence, Stag Arms, Bushmaster, and Rock River Arms (posts to the thread dated 1/23/2008).  Since 2008 new companies have come into the market (most notably Bravo Company and Daniel Defense) with very high quality products and CMMG’s reputation has suffered.  The carbine offered for sale here was purchased in February 2010, and since then CMMG seems to have let quality control slip in an effort to increase production.  The carbine for sale here (upper model U1605, lower model MOD4SA) is no longer for sale and new CMMG products should not be considered equal to products in the 2008-2010 window.  All this information can be found in postings on the thread introduced above, which is still active.

The features and specifications of this package and how they contribute to reliability follow:
>4150 grade steel barrel- harder and stronger than 4140 steel, meets military specification.
>Chrome lined chamber and bore- resists corrosion, easier to clean, very hard, naturally lubricating.  Some manufacturers are using Melonite surface conversion instead of chrome lining, but the military has been using chrome lining for more than 40 years.
>Government profile barrel weight- lightweight barrels can lose accuracy when they get hot, heavy barrel adds too much weight.  Government profile is the ideal in between weight for a fighting rifle.
>5.56 NATO chamber- can safely shoot .223 or 5.56, 5.56 should not be shot in a .223 chamber.  The 5.56 chamber is designed to chamber whatever is in the magazine, whereas the .223 chamber is intended for accuracy.  The 5.56 chamber is also designed for higher pressure limits.
>1/7 twist rate- allows the shooter to select bullet weights between 52 grains and 80 grains.  Heavier bullets mean harder hits on the target, a necessity in a fighting weapon.
>M4 feed ramps- Feed ramps are actually extended past the barrel into the upper receiver, and provide more reliable chambering of rounds from the magazine
>Magnetic particle inspected- a test that examines barrel (and bolt, in the case of this rifle) for microscopic flaws or cracks in the steel, after high pressure proof firing.
>Shot peened bolt- increases surface hardness of the steel.
>Midlength gas system- longer than the typical carbine length gas system on a 16” barrel, reduces gas pressure slightly to allow the carbine to cycle more smoothly than the carbine length gas system.
>F-marked front sight base- front sight base is high enough so that when sighted in the front sight is still protected by the ‘ears’ on the front sight base.  A sight that protrudes above the FSB can get bumped or broken during use, with obvious effects on accuracy.
>Properly staked gas key- the gas key must remain properly attached to the bolt carrier despite the shock of repeated recoil.  If the gas key works its way loose the carbine converts to single shot!
>Magpul Pmags- reliable magazines are a must to feed the carbine smoothly.  Pmags are highly recommended for their reliability and toughness.  This carbine comes with 20 round Pmags because it is very difficult to shoot from a rested position with the longer 30 round magazines.

Over a period of three years about 600 rounds have been fired through this carbine, both factory ammunition and handloads.  (Never any steel cased ammunition).  This means the rifle is used, but in no case is it worn.  These rifles are intended to fire many tens of thousands of rounds over their lifetime, so 600 rounds is barely broken in.  In fact, a typical one day defensive carbine course will put 600 rounds of ammunition through a carbine.  In addition, every one of those shots fed, fired, and ejected properly.  No stoppages.  This CMMG carbine is 100%, perfectly, reliable.  It is not a target rifle, it is a fighting carbine.  If you had to defend your family against home invaders, would you rather have a new gun that has never been fired or one which has been demonstrated to be reliable?

The scope on this carbine has an offset riser mount for optimum co-witness with the iron sights. It has flip-up caps and an integral sunshade, and red or green illumination. At 1x it behaves like a red dot, or it can be zoomed to take longer shots.  The sling plate has a curved loop that allows the sling hook to slide from one side to the other depending on what side you want to carry the carbine on.  Much easier to use than dual loop ambi sling plates.

You will be happy with this carbine.  I have been very happy with it, the only reason I am parting with it is to fund more hunting firearm purchases.  I would be happy to arrange a trade for LH bolt rifles, specifically 30-06 or .223.  

If you are interested text me at 336-eight eight zero-0 two seven one, or use the 'contact seller' button.  If you are distant and find this listing contact me and I will work with you to arrange payment/shipping to our mutual satisfaction.
